...a good-Iooking female reporter,
stashed on the roof covering Superman.

494
01:02:56,561 --> 01:03:00,226
- And you two are the ones with history.
- Chief, I've done Superman.

495
01:03:01,899 --> 01:03:03,939
Covered him. You know what I mean.

496
01:03:04,110 --> 01:03:06,268
Yeah, that makes you an expert.
Do him again.

497
01:03:06,445 --> 01:03:09,232
- There are a dozen other stories out there.
- Yeah? Name one.

498
01:03:09,407 --> 01:03:11,980
Well, there was a museum robbery
last night.

499
01:03:12,493 --> 01:03:15,944
Even Superman missed that one.
He was too busy saving this hooker.

500
01:03:16,121 --> 01:03:18,791
Why don't you guys
track down Lex Luthor?

501
01:03:19,500 --> 01:03:21,741
Well, no one's seen him
since his fifth appeal.

502
01:03:21,919 --> 01:03:24,077
He's got more history
with Superman than anyone.

503
01:03:24,254 --> 01:03:25,748
Maybe he's got something to say.

504
01:03:25,923 --> 01:03:29,671
- Luthor's yesterday's news.
- No, I like that idea.

505
01:03:30,636 --> 01:03:35,178
Perry, Lex Luthor is a career criminal
who nearly killed him, for God's sakes.

506
01:03:35,348 --> 01:03:37,590
Jimmy, how did Lex Luthor
get out of prison?

507
01:03:37,767 --> 01:03:41,765
Well, the appeals court called Superman
as a witness and he wasrt around.

508
01:03:42,480 --> 01:03:44,603
How much do you think
that pisses off Superman?

509
01:03:44,774 --> 01:03:46,399
- Give him to someone else.
- A lot.

510
01:03:46,568 --> 01:03:48,477
- A lot.
- Polly. Give him to Polly.

511
01:03:53,616 --> 01:03:55,158
Lois, Superman.

512
01:03:55,326 --> 01:03:57,533
- What about the blackout?
- Kent, blackout.

513
01:04:00,123 --> 01:04:02,448
Great. Thanks, chief.

514
01:04:05,586 --> 01:04:10,414
Lois, I'm sorry. I'd hate if this
damaged our relationship.

515
01:04:11,759 --> 01:04:12,874
Relationship?

516
01:04:13,636 --> 01:04:15,046
- Yeah.
- Hi, Mommy.

517
01:04:15,221 --> 01:04:17,094
- Hi, you.
- Hey, guys.

518
01:04:17,264 --> 01:04:21,048
He got an A in science, but a D in gym,
so we're doing something right.

519
01:04:21,226 --> 01:04:23,219
- Yeah, at least one of us is.
- What?

520
01:04:23,395 --> 01:04:26,230
It's Perry. He just shoved Superman
back into my life.

521
01:04:26,398 --> 01:04:29,352
Well, honey, I'm sure you can
find a way to interview Superman...

522
01:04:29,526 --> 01:04:31,519
...without bringing him
back into your life.

523
01:04:31,695 --> 01:04:35,989
There's really no way around it, folks.
Superman is back in all of our lives.

524
01:04:37,451 --> 01:04:39,242
We're coming to you from Sydney...

525
01:04:39,411 --> 01:04:43,195
...where people have gathered
on these rooftops to scour the sky...

526
01:04:43,373 --> 01:04:46,576
Okay, how about this?
We'll stay late. We'll get dinner.

527
01:04:46,751 --> 01:04:50,369
I'll help with Superman, and you and
Clark can work on the blackout together.

528
01:04:50,547 --> 01:04:53,501
- Is that all right with you, Clark?
- Swell.

529
01:05:17,406 --> 01:05:21,451
I was gonna pretend
the brakes were out.

530
01:05:21,619 --> 01:05:24,738
Pretend. Like we talked about.

531
01:05:24,913 --> 01:05:27,701
You didn't actually have to cut them!

532
01:05:27,875 --> 01:05:29,155
Of course I did.

533
01:05:29,334 --> 01:05:34,162
A man can always tell when a woman
is pretending, especially Superman.

534
01:05:39,052 --> 01:05:41,424
So did you get your rock?

535
01:05:42,806 --> 01:05:44,715
I did.

536
01:05:46,101 --> 01:05:50,145
U.S. Coast Guard issuing a small-craft
advisory for the Metropolis ocean area.

537
01:05:50,313 --> 01:05:52,140
High-wind advisory is in effect...

538
01:05:52,315 --> 01:05:55,186
...ocean currents and tides
becoming increasingly dangerous.

539
01:05:55,360 --> 01:05:58,563
All warnings lasting
until later this evening.

540
01:05:58,738 --> 01:05:59,983
Security, security.

541
01:06:00,156 --> 01:06:05,612
This is U.S. Coast Guard issuing
a small-craft advisory for northeast seas.

542
01:06:05,787 --> 01:06:10,247
Winds reaching 50 miles per hour,
high tides in the morning.

543
01:06:10,416 --> 01:06:12,243
Waves reaching 20 to 30 feet.

544
01:06:12,418 --> 01:06:16,416
This warning is in effect for
all small crafts for the next four hours.

545
01:06:40,529 --> 01:06:42,153
Weird. If these times are right...

546
01:06:42,322 --> 01:06:45,406
...the blackout spread
from a specific origin point.

547
01:06:45,575 --> 01:06:46,951
Where?

548
01:06:47,119 --> 01:06:48,910
I'm not sure yet.

549
01:06:49,621 --> 01:06:53,286
With the super-hearing, does he hear each
sound by itself or everything at once?

550
01:06:53,667 --> 01:06:54,912
Both.

551
01:06:55,085 --> 01:06:57,291
- He's certainly taller than I thought.
- 6'4".

552
01:06:57,462 --> 01:07:01,210
I love that he can see through anything.
I'd have fun with that.

553
01:07:01,591 --> 01:07:03,299
Anything but lead.

554
01:07:06,554 --> 01:07:07,799
- I bet he's...
- 225 pounds...

555
01:07:07,972 --> 01:07:09,632
...faster than a speeding bullet...

556
01:07:09,807 --> 01:07:13,259
...draws his power from the sun,
invulnerable to anything but kryptonite...

557
01:07:13,436 --> 01:07:15,475
...and he never lies.
- Kryptonite?

558
01:07:15,646 --> 01:07:17,971
Radioactive pieces of his home world.

559
01:07:18,149 --> 01:07:20,355
It's deadly. To him.

560
01:07:24,947 --> 01:07:28,316
Lois, how tall would you say Clark is?

561
01:07:29,868 --> 01:07:31,861
About 6'3", 6'4".

562
01:07:32,037 --> 01:07:34,824
About 200, 215 pounds?

563
01:07:44,800 --> 01:07:48,797
Jimmy, Jason, let's go get these intrepid
reporters something to keep them going.

564
01:07:48,970 --> 01:07:50,844
- Burritos!
- Come here, canead.

565
01:07:52,349 --> 01:07:56,298
We're going this way. Do they have
anything other than burritos?

566
01:07:57,187 --> 01:07:59,512
I think they have fries and burgers.

567
01:07:59,689 --> 01:08:02,180
So have you found a place to live yet?

568
01:08:02,358 --> 01:08:03,936
No. I'm still looking.

569
01:08:04,694 --> 01:08:07,185
You know, Lois, I wanted to ask you
about that artic...

570
01:08:07,363 --> 01:08:10,863
Hey, I'm gonna run downstairs
for some fresh air. Great!

571
01:08:24,630 --> 01:08:26,338
Thanks.

572
01:08:34,139 --> 01:08:36,891
- Let's talk when I get back.
- Sure.

573
01:09:30,403 --> 01:09:33,154
You know, you really
shouldn't smoke, Miss Lane.

574
01:09:36,450 --> 01:09:38,941
- Sorry. Didrt mean to startle you.
- I'm fine. Really.

575
01:09:41,080 --> 01:09:44,199
I just wasrt expecting you.

576
01:09:44,875 --> 01:09:46,453
With all the press on the plane...

577
01:09:46,627 --> 01:09:49,034
...I wasrt sure it was
the best time for us to talk.

578
01:09:49,213 --> 01:09:52,379
Well, there's no press around now.
Except for me, of course.

579
01:09:54,593 --> 01:09:57,048
I know people are asking questions
now that I'm back.

580
01:09:57,429 --> 01:10:00,964
I think it's only fair
that I answer those people.

581
01:10:02,642 --> 01:10:05,976
So you're here for an interview?

582
01:10:07,230 --> 01:10:08,261
Okay, then.

583
01:10:12,152 --> 01:10:14,144
- Where did I put that thing?
- Right pocket.

584
01:10:20,284 --> 01:10:22,989
Let's start with the big question.

585
01:10:23,162 --> 01:10:25,653
- Where'd you go?
- To Krypton.

586
01:10:25,832 --> 01:10:28,204
But you told me it was destroyed.
Ages ago.

587
01:10:28,376 --> 01:10:29,834
It was.

588
01:10:30,002 --> 01:10:32,374
But when astronomers
thought they found it...

589
01:10:33,839 --> 01:10:36,211
...I had to see for myself.

590
01:10:39,845 --> 01:10:43,677
Well, you're back, and everyone
seems to be pretty happy about it.

591
01:10:46,894 --> 01:10:48,352
Not everyone.

592
01:10:49,521 --> 01:10:51,929
- I read the article, Lois.
- So did a lot of people.

593
01:10:52,107 --> 01:10:55,061
- Tomorrow they're giving me the Pulitzer...
- Why did you write it?

594
01:10:56,737 --> 01:10:58,776
How could you leave us like that?

595
01:11:00,282 --> 01:11:02,689
I moved on. So did the rest of us.

596
01:11:03,201 --> 01:11:04,695
That's why I wrote it.

597
01:11:04,870 --> 01:11:07,657
The world doesn't need a savior.

598
01:11:08,081 --> 01:11:09,990
And neither do I.

599
01:11:25,139 --> 01:11:26,218
Lois.

600
01:11:27,934 --> 01:11:30,389
Will you come with me?

601
01:11:32,146 --> 01:11:33,724
Why?

602
01:11:34,106 --> 01:11:36,229
There's something I wanna show you.

603
01:11:42,489 --> 01:11:44,281
Please.

604
01:11:55,294 --> 01:11:57,452
I can't be gone long.

605
01:11:57,629 --> 01:11:59,538
You won't be.

606
01:12:11,935 --> 01:12:14,686
Clark said the reason you left
without saying goodbye...

607
01:12:14,854 --> 01:12:17,143
...is because it was
too unbearable for you.

608
01:12:17,315 --> 01:12:19,936
Personally, I think that's a load of crap.

609
01:12:20,527 --> 01:12:23,693
- Clark?
- He's just a guy I work with.

610
01:12:24,781 --> 01:12:26,904
Maybe Clark's right.

611
01:12:30,286 --> 01:12:32,409
You know, my...

612
01:12:32,580 --> 01:12:37,621
Richard, he's a pilot.
He takes me up all the time.

613
01:12:38,794 --> 01:12:40,787
Not like this.

614
01:12:55,644 --> 01:12:58,052
I forgot how warm you were.

615
01:13:28,676 --> 01:13:30,170
Listen.

616
01:13:31,054 --> 01:13:32,963
What do you hear?

617
01:13:33,681 --> 01:13:34,926
Nothing.

618
01:13:38,853 --> 01:13:40,596
I hear everything.

619
01:13:44,066 --> 01:13:46,688
You wrote that the world
doesn't need a savior...

620
01:13:48,028 --> 01:13:51,362
...but every day
I hear people crying for one.

621
01:14:04,211 --> 01:14:06,880
I'm sorry I left you, Lois.

622
01:14:10,759 --> 01:14:12,798
I'll take you back now.

623
01:16:25,932 --> 01:16:27,557
Richard's a good man.

624
01:16:30,979 --> 01:16:33,185
And you've been gone a long time.

625
01:16:35,858 --> 01:16:37,436
I know.

626
01:16:42,198 --> 01:16:43,526
L...

627
01:16:48,746 --> 01:16:50,739
So will I see you around?

628
01:16:51,749 --> 01:16:53,742
I'm always around.

629
01:16:55,044 --> 01:16:56,752
Good night, Lois.

630
01:17:15,731 --> 01:17:19,598
We're having beef, honey. Do you want
the tofu wrap or the veggie wrap?

631
01:17:23,405 --> 01:17:24,982
You all right?

632
01:17:26,825 --> 01:17:28,236
Where have you been?

633
01:17:32,580 --> 01:17:38,251
I was up on the roof, getting some air.

634
01:17:38,920 --> 01:17:40,877
Tell the truth now.

635
01:17:47,428 --> 01:17:48,591
Were you smoking?

636
01:17:51,224 --> 01:17:52,967
No.

637
01:18:01,775 --> 01:18:02,974
Is this real?

638
01:18:04,028 --> 01:18:05,901
- Where'd you find him?
- He found me.

639
01:18:06,071 --> 01:18:08,858
Oh, this is great. I can't wait to read it.

640
01:18:09,033 --> 01:18:11,440
So, Mr. White, about the blackout...

641
01:18:11,618 --> 01:18:14,109
Lois, this is the biggest night
of your life.

642
01:18:14,288 --> 01:18:16,446
Have you picked out a dress?
Something snazzy?

643
01:18:17,457 --> 01:18:20,162
It just feels a little weird
winning for that article.

644
01:18:20,335 --> 01:18:23,372
- It just doesn't seem right.
- What doesn't seem right?

645
01:18:23,547 --> 01:18:27,129
Winning an award for an article called
"Why the World Doesrt Need Superman."

646
01:18:27,300 --> 01:18:29,756
When, according
to this newspaper, they do.

647
01:18:29,928 --> 01:18:32,845
Lois, Pulitzer Prizes
are like Academy Awards.

648
01:18:33,014 --> 01:18:36,134
Nobody remembers what you got one for.
It's just that you got one.

649
01:18:36,309 --> 01:18:39,429
- But...
- This is your night. You enjoy it.

650
01:18:39,604 --> 01:18:42,142
I'm sure Kent's on the blackout.

651
01:19:42,796 --> 01:19:45,002
Department of Water and Power, please.

652
01:19:45,716 --> 01:19:46,996
7782, great.

653
01:19:48,468 --> 01:19:49,962
Metropolis Public Works.

654
01:19:50,137 --> 01:19:52,628
Hi, Stephen, Lois Lane
from the Daily Planet. Blackout?

655
01:19:52,806 --> 01:19:55,511
I just need a little info
on a few outstanding power grids.

656
01:19:55,684 --> 01:19:57,308
Yeah, I do have it here, actually.

657
01:19:57,477 --> 01:20:01,475
So the uptown grid went dark at 12:36
and midtown 10 seconds before.

658
01:20:01,648 --> 01:20:03,142
Which grid was hit first?

659
01:20:03,316 --> 01:20:04,645
It just reads Vanderwon'th.

660
01:20:04,818 --> 01:20:07,190
- Across the river?
- 6 Springwood Drive.

661
01:20:07,362 --> 01:20:09,604
6 Springwood Drive.
A residence or a business?

662
01:20:09,781 --> 01:20:11,524
- Residence.
- Sure? Nothing before that?

663
01:20:11,700 --> 01:20:14,025
- That's all it shows.
- Thank you very much.

664
01:20:15,870 --> 01:20:17,151
Oh, Jason.

665
01:20:23,962 --> 01:20:27,165
- There's your mom, Jason.
- You're late, Mommy.

666
01:20:35,390 --> 01:20:38,225
Where are we? Is this the Pulitzer?

667
01:20:38,393 --> 01:20:42,686
Nope. I've just gotta ask these people
a few questions and then we can go.

668
01:20:56,994 --> 01:20:59,367
Can I stay in the car?

669
01:20:59,914 --> 01:21:01,492
No, honey.

670
01:21:08,172 --> 01:21:12,549
- Are we trespassing?
- No. Yes.

671
01:21:27,274 --> 01:21:29,101
Hello?

672
01:22:00,599 --> 01:22:02,141
Hello?

673
01:22:13,236 --> 01:22:15,810
I like the curly one.

674
01:22:23,121 --> 01:22:25,956
Let's go. This was a bad idea.

675
01:22:41,681 --> 01:22:43,473
Lex Luthor.

676
01:22:45,477 --> 01:22:47,600
Lois Lane?

677
01:22:53,401 --> 01:22:54,730
You're bald.

678
01:23:14,839 --> 01:23:16,214
And what is your name?

679
01:23:16,382 --> 01:23:18,838
I'm not supposed to talk to strangers.

680
01:23:19,343 --> 01:23:21,301
- Cute kid, and smart.
- Thanks.

681
01:23:21,471 --> 01:23:24,674
We're not really strangers, are we?
This is kind of a little reunion.

682
01:23:24,849 --> 01:23:26,888
Heck, I'm a fan.

683
01:23:27,059 --> 01:23:28,554
I love your writing...

684
01:23:29,395 --> 01:23:31,222
...and your dress.
- I love your boat.

685
01:23:31,397 --> 01:23:34,018
How'd you get it?
Swindle some widow out of her money?

686
01:23:35,359 --> 01:23:37,601
That's funny. Didrt you win
the Pulitzer Prize...

687
01:23:37,778 --> 01:23:41,361
...for my favorite article of all time, " Why
the World Doesrt Need Superman"?

688
01:23:41,532 --> 01:23:45,446
Didrt you have a few more years to go
on that double life sentence?

689
01:23:45,619 --> 01:23:47,861
Yes, well, we can thank
the Man of Steel for that.

690
01:23:48,039 --> 01:23:51,324
I mean, he's really good at swooping in
and catching the bad guys...

691
01:23:51,500 --> 01:23:55,035
...but he's not so hot at the little things,
like Miranda rights...

692
01:23:55,212 --> 01:23:59,921
...due process, making your court date.

693
01:24:00,092 --> 01:24:02,548
Did you have anything to do
with the blackout?

694
01:24:05,556 --> 01:24:07,762
Are you fishing for an interview,
Miss Lane?

695
01:24:07,933 --> 01:24:10,092
It's been a while
since you've been a headline.

696
01:24:10,269 --> 01:24:12,427
Maybe it's time
people knew your name again.

697
01:24:13,105 --> 01:24:17,055
How about we turn this boat around,
call a cab for my son...

698
01:24:17,609 --> 01:24:20,231
...and then you can do
whatever you want with me.

699
01:24:20,946 --> 01:24:23,484
No, I don't think we'll be
turning around, Miss Lane...

700
01:24:23,657 --> 01:24:26,278
...which means that
we do have some time to kill.

701
01:24:28,453 --> 01:24:30,327
How about that interview?

702
01:24:31,248 --> 01:24:34,581
Yeah, just call me if you hear anything.
Okay. Thank you.

703
01:24:34,751 --> 01:24:36,459
So, what did the school say?

704
01:24:36,628 --> 01:24:38,122
She picked him up at 3: 15.

705
01:24:42,384 --> 01:24:45,669
- Hi, I heard about Lois.
- Yes, come in, Clark, come in.

706
01:24:45,846 --> 01:24:48,337
- Is there anything I can do?
- Yeah, you're a reporter.

707
01:24:48,515 --> 01:24:51,267
- Help Richard track her down.
- I'll check her computer.

708
01:24:51,435 --> 01:24:52,680
Excuse me, Clark.

709
01:25:06,408 --> 01:25:09,492
What do you know about crystals?

710
01:25:09,661 --> 01:25:11,369
They make great chandeliers.

711
01:25:11,955 --> 01:25:16,949
This crystal may seem unremarkable,
but so is the seed of a redwood tree.

712
01:25:17,127 --> 01:25:20,542
It's how our mutual friend in tights
made his Arctic getaway spot.

713
01:25:20,714 --> 01:25:22,587
Cute. It's a little small for my taste.

714
01:25:22,757 --> 01:25:24,299
You're building an island?

715
01:25:25,510 --> 01:25:28,843
You're not seeing
the big picture here, Miss Lane.

716
01:25:29,013 --> 01:25:31,302
Let me enlarge it for you.

717
01:25:33,893 --> 01:25:37,309
Not just an island,
an entirely new continent.

718
01:25:37,480 --> 01:25:40,730
An extinct world, reborn on our own.

719
01:25:40,900 --> 01:25:42,311
Why?

720
01:25:45,321 --> 01:25:47,230
Land, Miss Lane.

721
01:25:47,407 --> 01:25:50,158
I mean... Kitty, what did my father
used to say to me?

722
01:25:50,326 --> 01:25:51,737
"You're losing your hair"?

723
01:25:52,745 --> 01:25:54,654
- Before that.
- "Get out"?

724
01:25:56,207 --> 01:25:58,496
He said, " You can print money...

725
01:25:58,668 --> 01:26:01,289
...manufacture diamonds,
and people are a dime a dozen...

726
01:26:01,462 --> 01:26:04,546
...but they'll always need land."

727
01:26:04,715 --> 01:26:07,550
It's the one thing
they're not making any more of.

728
01:26:08,094 --> 01:26:10,466
But the United States...

729
01:26:12,181 --> 01:26:15,680
Will be underwater.

730
01:26:16,102 --> 01:26:17,679
It's simple physics, Miss Lane.

731
01:26:17,853 --> 01:26:20,640
Two objects cannot occupy
the same space at the same time.

732
01:26:20,815 --> 01:26:23,353
And the rest of the world
will just let you keep it?

733
01:26:23,526 --> 01:26:25,732
- They'Il...
- They'II...

734
01:26:26,237 --> 01:26:27,695
...what?

735
01:26:27,863 --> 01:26:30,734
I'll have advanced alien technology...

736
01:26:30,908 --> 01:26:33,944
...thousands of years beyond
what anyone could throw at me.

737
01:26:34,119 --> 01:26:36,159
Bring it on!

738
01:26:37,164 --> 01:26:39,073
And eventually...

739
01:26:39,249 --> 01:26:41,575
